Q1. What is Linux Operating System(OS)?

Linux is a free, open-source, Unix-like operating system kernel first created by Linus Torvalds in 1991. Over time, it evolved into a complete operating system when combined with GNU software tools,libraries,and applications.

It functions just like any other OS, it manages the hardware resources of a computer(CPU, meomry,storage,devices) and provides an environment where applications can run.

Linux is available in different distributions(distros) such as Ubuntu,Fedora,Kali Linux,Debian, and Red Hat, each designed for specific purposes like general use, security testing, or servers.

It is widely used in:

->Servers and supercomputers (majority of the web servers run on Linux).
-> Embedded systems.(Routers,IoT devices, Android phones)
-> Cybersecurity & Networking(Kali Linux, Parrot OS).
-> Software development(Programming and DevOps environments).

Pros:

-> Open-source & Free- No licensing cost,Users can modify the code as per their needs.
-> Security & Stability- Less vulnerable to malware and viruses compared to other OS.
-> Performance & Flexibility- Lightweight,runs efficiently even on older hardware, and can be customized for servers, desktops, or embedded systems.

Cons:

-> Software Compatibility Issues- Many commercial software and games are not directly available(though alternatives or workarounds exist).
-> Learning Curve- New users may find command-line usage and system administration challenging.
-> Hardware/Driver Support- Some hardware(like printers, Wi-Fi adapters, or graphics cards)may have limited driver support.

Q2. Differentiate between Linux, Mac, Android, and Windows OS with at least six unique features.

1. Linux:

-> It is open-source(free,modifiable).
-> It is free of cost.
-> The user interface is highly customizable(varies by distro & desktop environment).
-> It supports widerange of hardware,may require manual driver installation.
-> It is highly secure and less prone to viruses.
-> It is a large section of free/open-source software, but limited commercial apps.
-> It is highly flexible,we can modify the kernel,GUI and many other services.
-> It is lightweight and efficient,can run on older hardware.
-> Used in servers, developers, cybersecurity, embedded systems.

2. MacOS:

-> It is a closed proprietary.
-> It is a paid source and only comes with apple devices.
-> The userinterface is consitent,polished,and  user-friendly GUI
-> This OS can only be integrated with apple devices because only Apple devices have the hardware compatibility for this OS.
-> It is very secure due to Unix-based architecture.
-> It is best for Apple ecosystem apps.
-> Limited customisation because the Apple company controls the OS features.
-> Optimized for Apple hardware.
-> Used for creative work (graphics, video, music), macOS apps, Apple ecosystem.

3. Android:

-> It is an open-source core but most devices have proprietary layers.
-> The OS is free, cost depends on device.
-> The user interface is touch-based GUI optimized for mobile.
-> It runs on ARM processors,works on smartphones, tablets, some TVs.
-> It is secure but depends on app store and device manufacturer.
-> It has a huge app ecosystem via Google Play,mostly mobile apps.
-> It is moderately customizable through settings and launchers.
-> It is optimised for mobile devices,battery efficient.
-> USed in smartphones, tablets, IoT, embedded systems.

4. Windows:

-> It is a Closed proprietary.
-> It is a paid source but there are some free editions.
-> The user interface is GUI with start menu and task bar,and is moderately customizable.
-> It works on x86/x64 PCs, has wide hardware support and has plug-and-play drivers.
-> It is more vulnerable to malware and viruses.
-> It has the widest software support and supports most commercial applications and games.
-> It has moderate customization, themes, settings, but kernel is fixed.
-> It has moderate performance, can be resource heavy on older hardware.
-> Used in general-purpose computers,gaming, business, education.

Q3. Why is Linux preferred for Mainframe Servers for legacy application? Give three out-of-the-box technical reasons.

Linux is widely preferred for mainframe servers and legacy applications because of its:

1. Enhanced Security and Access Control:

-> Linux provides fine-grained user permissions and role-based access control, reducing the risk of unauthorized access to critical legacy applications.
-> SELinux (Security-Enhanced Linux) adds an extra layer of mandatory access control, which is crucial for enterprise mainframes handling sensitive data.
->Regular security patches and strong kernel-level protections make it a trusted choice for legacy systems that require long-term security.

2. Cost-Effectiveness and Open-Source Flexibility:

->Unlike proprietary mainframe OS (like z/OS), Linux is open-source and free, which significantly reduces licensing costs for large-scale mainframe deployments.
->Companies can customize the kernel, remove unnecessary modules, or optimize resource usage to suit legacy workloads.
->This makes it feasible to extend the lifespan of legacy applications without being locked into expensive vendor ecosystems.

3. Support for Modern Virtualization and Containers:

->Linux has native support for virtualization technologies like KVM (Kernel-based Virtual Machine) and containerization (Docker, Podman).
->Legacy applications can be isolated in containers or virtual machines, making migration, testing, and scaling much easier on mainframes.
->This ensures that even old applications can run alongside modern workloads without conflicts, maximizing hardware utilization.

Q4. Explain the structure of the Linux File System with proper diagram.

1. Overview of Linux File System:

->The Linux file system is organized in a hierarchical (tree-like) structure, starting from the root directory '/'. Every file and directory is a child of '/'.
->Linux uses directories to organize files.
->Everything is treated as a file, including hardware devices and processes.
->Standard directories are defined by the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard (FHS).

2. Common Directories in Linux:
-> /	  ~Root directory, top of the hierarchy.
-> /bin	  ~Essential binaries (commands) needed by all users (e.g., ls, cp).
-> /sbin  ~System binaries for administrative tasks (e.g., ifconfig, fsck).
-> /boot  ~Contains kernel and bootloader files.
-> /dev	  ~Device files (e.g., /dev/sda for storage devices).
-> /etc	  ~Configuration files for the system and applications.
-> /home  ~User home directories (e.g., /home/mohan).
-> /lib	  ~Shared libraries required by binaries in /bin and /sbin.
-> /opt	  ~Optional software and add-on packages.
-> /tmp	  ~Temporary files.
-> /usr	  ~User programs, libraries, and documentation.
-> /var	  ~Variable data like logs, mail, spool files.
-> /media ~Mount point for removable media (USB, CD-ROM).
-> /mnt	  ~Temporary mount point for filesystems.
-> /proc  ~Virtual filesystem for system and process information.
-> /sys	  ~Kernel interface for devices and system info.

